<br>
Folks in small guilds, or who are guildless, have a hard time organizing raids.  They tend to have a more limited number of targets as well (the first floor of Plane of Hate is a fair raid for a green group of high 40's/low 50's.  The higher Planes in PoP, or even places like the Halls of Testing, are simply out of their range.)  These are the folks who benifit from a reservation system.  It gives them a chance to plan their events, and in a guild/alliance/open raid that lacks expereince with organization, this can be vital.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, folks in raiding guilds and higher-end alliances pay the same money each month to gain access to the same content as the little guys.  They want their epics to, and have just as much right to hunt in Plane of Hate as the small guild who needs a week to prepare.  From their point of view, there is nothing stopping the small guild folks from building up their alliances, or even joining a stronger guild, just as they did.<br>
<br>
Now personally, I think the fairest path is somewhere in the middle.  The general consensus on open raids seems to be that guilds will give them special consideration, allowing them a shot at a zone or a mob without a race to gather raid forces.  I think this is a good thing, and the right approach.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, the number of closed raids posted here in recent weeks vastly outnumbers the amount of open raids.  And I do not think a closed raid from an up and coming alliance should be treated any differently than a closed raid from an established guild.<br>
<br>
This is where I part company with the majority of folks who post here, I expect.  If Resolution (not to pick on anyone, or to even suggest they would ever do this) posted here that they planned on going to PoH next Thursday in a closed raid for epic mobs, should other guilds capable of doing Hate, who also need epic drops, honor this?  Why does a guild posting here have more right to the content than a guild that does not read these boards at all?<br>
<br>
Now narrow this down to the smaller picture.  An alliance that is quite capable of raiding the Halls of Testing, Kael, Kunark dragons, etc... posts here that they intend to go to Hate next Thursday in a closed raid for epic drops.  Should other guilds honor their intention, when they have players who need those drops to?  <br>
<br>
This is where reservation systems start to break down--when guilds and alliances outgrow the open-raid stage, but continue to try and take advantage of the system.  The more established guilds view this as gaming the system, and after a while simply start to ignore reservations.  The up and coming guys feel they are doing nothing wrong, this is how it has always been done, and this kind of reservation system keeps the server from degenerating into chaos.  Which side is right?  Hard to say.  But I hope folks on both sides of this issue will consider the other's position, and not simply label them as greedy for disagreeing with your own.<br>
. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sirdo>Sirdo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Self-proclaimed defender of <br>the little guys
