<br>
Certainly, first come first served is in the self-interest of established raiding guilds.  But I don't think it is fair to malign their honor for it.  While it may well end up preventing some lower level guilds or alliances from getting the mob or zone they want from time to time, a reservation system has the same effect on the raiding guilds.  Both are driven by self interest, so I do not feel it is fair to charetorize one as honorable and the other as not.<br>
<br>
Further, I think the reservation systems have a tendency to collapse under their own weight after a while.  Let's say a guild alliance uses the reservation system here.  They use it quite often, so often in fact that nearly every weekend they are in either Plane of Hate or Plane of Fear.  Now, is it fair to other guilds who would also like to do those planes that the system is used thus?  <br>
<br>
And what if the guilds who comprise the allainces also &quot;book&quot; dates individually?  With the result that some folks are effectively enjoying one or other old-world plane each weekend, while the rest of the server are left twiddling their thumbs and complaining about their lack of access to epic mobs?   I am *not* arguing that this is happening here, but it did happen on my old server (Innoruuk) and it wrecked the reservation system we enjoyed for several years.<br>
<br>
And is their a limit on what can be booked?  I've seen the level 52 dragons, chardok royals, Planes of Hate, Fear, and Sky, the Junk Beast in plane of Innovation, various Luclin mobs, etc... all be &quot;reserved&quot; here.  Should the reservation system apply to everything?  Should raiding guilds ignore the dragon that is up for 4 days so that they might honor the booking of a guild that can only kill it on weekends?<br>
<br>
And the booking system sets up a situation where it is implied that small guilds or alliances somehow have more right to a reservable-mob or epic drop than the raiding guilds.  Obviously, this does not sit very well with the bigger guilds.  Everyone pays the same amount per month to play the game, and many would argue that everyone, regardless of their willingness to peruse message boards, deserves the same access to content.  <br>
<br>
I am enormously sympathetic to the plight of small guilds.  I prefer them, they are less headache and more fun.  Heck, I've been guildless on this server for 55 levels, so I obviously have no need to take the side of raiding guilds out of my own self interest.  I simply think the reservation system is getting out of hand, and if folks do not become a bit more reasonable in their expectations of it, it is going to collapse under its own weight.<br>
<br>
If you are organizing an open, or even semi-open raid, and post here, I think nearly everyone would honor it.  That is the way it should be.  But I do not think that any private guild raid, closed alliance raid, etc... deserves any special treatment, whether it is posted here or not.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sirdo>Sirdo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Self-proclaimed defender of <br>the little guys
